org.goobi.mq

Class ActiveMQDirector

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.goobi.mq.ActiveMQDirector
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    EventListener, javax.jms.ExceptionListener, javax.servlet.ServletContextListener

    public class ActiveMQDirector
extends Object
implements javax.servlet.ServletContextListener, javax.jms.ExceptionListener
    The class ActiveMQDirector is the head of all Active MQ processors. It implements the ServletContextListener interface and is − if configured in web.xml − called automatically upon server starup. Its job is to connect to the Active MQ server and register the listeners configured.

    The ActiveMQDirector should ALWAYS be declared in web.xml. The Active MQ services are intended to be run in case that “activeMQ.hostURL” is configured in the kitodo_config.properties file. To disable the service, the entry there should be emptied or commented out. Otherwise, a valid configuration would not start working and an administrator will hardly have a chance to find out why without inspecting the source code.

    The class ActiveMQDirector also provides a basic ExceptionListener implementation as required for the connection.

    Author:
    Matthias Ronge <matthias.ronge@zeutschel.de>

      • connectToServer

        protected javax.jms.Session connectToServer(String server)
        Sets up a connection to an active MQ server. The connection object is global because it is needed later to shut down the connection.
        Parameters:
        server - should be “tcp://{host}:{port}” or “vm://localhost” in case that the server is run inside the same virtual machine
        Returns:
        the session object or “null” upon error

      • registerListeners

        protected void registerListeners(ActiveMQProcessor[] processors)
        This method registers the listeners with the active MQ server.

        If a queue name was configured for a service, a MessageConsumer is set up to listen on that queue and, in case of incoming messages, make the service process the message. The message checker is saved inside the service to be able to shut it down later.

      • setUpReportChannel

        protected javax.jms.MessageProducer setUpReportChannel(String topic)
        This sets up a connection to the topic the results shall be written to. The delivery mode is set so “persistent” to allow consumers not online with the server in the moment of message submission to read the messages later. The log messages are set to be kept on the server for 7 days. This value can be overridden from the kitodo_config.properties parameter “activeMQ.results.timeToLive”. The time to live must be specified in milliseconds; 0 disables the oblivion. (See also: http://docs.oracle.com/javaee/6/api/javax/jms/MessageProducer.html#setTimeToLive%28long%29 )
        Parameters:
        topic - name of the active MQ topic
        Returns:
        a MessageProducer object ready for writing or “null” on error
